]] = [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]]\n|[[Budha]]v\u0101ra <br/> \u092c\u0941\u0927\u0935\u093e\u0930\n|[[Budha|Buddh]] <br/> \u092c\u0941\u0927\n|[[Budha|Buddhav\u0101r]] <br/> \u0a2c\u0a41\u0a71\u0a27\u0a35\u0a3e\u0a30\n|[[Budha|Budhb\u0101r]] <br/> \u09ac\u09c1\u09a7\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\n|[[Budha|Budb\u0101r]] <br/> {{font|\ua81b\ua825\ua817\ua806\ua81b\ua823\ua81e|font=Surma|size=18px}}\n|[[Budha|Buidbar]]\n|[[Budha|Budhb\u0101r]] <br/> \u09ac\u09c1\u09a7\u09ac\u09be\u09f0\n|[[Budha]]v\u0101ra <br/> \u092c\u0941\u0927\u0935\u093e\u0930 \n|[[Budha]]bar <br/> \u092c\u0941\u0927\u0935\u093e\u0930\n|[[Budha|Budh\u00f4b\u0101r\u00f4]] <br/> \u0b2c\u0b41\u0b27\u0b2c\u0b3e\u0b30\n|[[Budha]]v\u0101ra <br/> \u0cac\u0cc1\u0ca7\u0cb5\u0cbe\u0cb0\n|[[Budha]]v\u0101ra\u1e41 <br/> \u0c2c\u0c41\u0c27\u0c35\u0c3e\u0c30\u0c02 \n|[[Budha]]n <br/>  \u0baa\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0ba9\u0bcd\n|[[Budha]]n  <br/> \u0d2c\u0d41\u0d27\u0d7b \n|[[Budha]]v\u0101r <br/> \u0aac\u0ac1\u0aa7\u0ab5\u0abe\u0ab0\n|B\u00f6dv\u0101r<br />\u092c\u0945\u0926\u0935\u093e\u0930 {{Nastaliq| \u0628\u0631\u06be \u0648\u0627\u0631}}\n|-\n|5\n|[[Guru]]v\u0101sara <br/> \u0917\u0941\u0930\u0941\u0935\u093e\u0938\u0930 <br/> or <br> [[Brihaspati|Brhaspati]] v\u0101sara <br/> \u092c\u0943\u0939\u0938\u094d\u092a\u0924\u093f\u0935\u093e\u0938\u0930\n|[[Thursday]]/dies [[Jupiter (mythology)|Iovis]]/Jupiter\n|[[B\u1e5bhaspati|Deva-Guru B\u1e5bhaspati]] = [[Jupiter]]\n|[[Guru]]v\u0101r <br/> \u0917\u0941\u0930\u0941\u0935\u093e\u0930 or <br> [[Brihaspati]]v\u0101ra <br> \u092c\u0943\u0939\u0938\u094d\u092a\u0924\u093f\u0935\u093e\u0930\n|[[Guru|Bi'phey]] <br/> \u092c\u093f\u092f\u092b\u0947\n|[[Guru|V\u012brav\u0101r]] <br/> \u0a35\u0a40\u0a30\u0a35\u0a3e\u0a30\n|[[Guru|Brih\u00f4\u015bp\u00f4tib\u0101r]] <br/> \u09ac\u09c3\u09b9\u09b8\u09cd\u09aa\u09a4\u09bf\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\n|[[Guru|Bir\u00f4i\u015b\u00f4tb\u0101r]] <br/> {{font|\ua81b\ua824?\ua81b\ua823\ua81e|font=Surma|size=18px}}\n|[[Guru|Bic\u00edbbar]]\n|[[Guru|Brih\u00f4sp\u00f4tib\u0101r]] <br/> \u09ac\u09c3\u09b9\u09b8\u09cd\u09aa\u09a4\u09bf\u09ac\u09be\u09f0\n|[[Guru]]v\u0101ra <br/> \u0917\u0941\u0930\u0941\u0935\u093e\u0930\n|[[Guru|Bihibar]] <br/> \u092c\u093f\u0939\u093f\u0935\u093e\u0930\n|[[Guru]]b\u0101r\u00f4 <br/> \u0b17\u0b41\u0b30\u0b41\u0b2c\u0b3e\u0b30\n|[[Guru]]v\u0101ra <br/> \u0c97\u0cc1\u0cb0\u0cc1\u0cb5\u0cbe\u0cb0\n|[[Guru|Guruv\u0101ra\u1e41, Br\u0325haspativ\u0101ra\u1e41]] <br/> \u0c17\u0c41\u0c30\u0c41\u0c35\u0c3e\u0c30\u0c02, \u0c2c\u0c43\u0c39\u0c38\u0c4d\u0c2a\u0c24\u0c3f\u0c35\u0c3e\u0c30\u0c02, \u0c32\u0c15\u0c4d\u0c37\u0c4d\u0c2e\u0c40\u0c35\u0c3e\u0c30\u0c02 \n|[[Guru|Vyazhan]] <br/> \u0bb5\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbe\u0bb4\u0ba9\u0bcd\n|[[Guru|Vyaazham]]  <br/> \u0d35\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d3e\u0d34\u0d02 \n|[[Guru]]v\u0101r <br/> \u0a97\u0ac1\u0ab0\u0ac1\u0ab5\u0abe\u0ab0\n|Br\u00easv\u0101r  <br />\u092c\u094d\u0930\u0938\u0935\u093e\u0930 {{Nastaliq| \u0628\u0631\u0633 \u0648\u0627\u0631}}\n|-\n|6\n|[[Shukra|\u015aukra]]v\u0101sara <br/> \u0936\u0941\u0915\u094d\u0930\u0935\u093e\u0938\u0930\n|[[Friday]]/dies [[Venus (mythology)|Veneris]]\n|[[Shukra|\u015aukra]] = [[Venus]]\n|[[Shukra|\u015aukrav\u0101r]] <br/> \u0936\u0941\u0915\u094d\u0930\u0935\u093e\u0930\n|[[Shukra|Sukkar]] <br/> \u0938\u0941\u0915\u094d\u0915\u0930\n|[[Shukra|\u015aukkarav\u0101r]] <br/> \u0a38\u0a3c\u0a41\u0a71\u0a15\u0a30\u0a35\u0a3e\u0a30\n|[[Shukra|\u015aukr\u00f4b\u0101r]] <br/> \u09b6\u09c1\u0995\u09cd\u09b0\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\n|[[Shukra|\u015aukkurb\u0101r]] <br/> {{font|\ua821\ua825\ua807\ua806\ua807\ua825\ua81e\ua806\ua81b\ua823\ua81e/\ua80e\ua825\ua81d\ua806\ua81d\ua823\ua81b\ua823\ua81e|font=Surma|size=18px}}\n|[[Shukra|C\u00fakkurbar]]\n|[[Shukra|Xukurb\u0101r/Xukr\u00f4b\u0101r]] <br/> \u09b6\u09c1\u0995\u09c1\u09f0\u09ac\u09be\u09f0/\u09b6\u09c1\u0995\u09cd\u09b0\u09ac\u09be\u09f0\n|[[Shukra|\u015aukrav\u0101ra]] <br/> \u0936\u0941\u0915\u094d\u0930\u0935\u093e\u0930\n|[[Shukra|Sukrabar]] <br/> \u0936\u0941\u0915\u094d\u0930\u0935\u093e\u0930\n|[[Shukra|\u015aukr\u00f4b\u0101r\u00f4]] <br/> \u0b36\u0b41\u0b15\u0b4d\u0b30\u0b2c\u0b3e\u0b30\n|[[Shukra|\u015aukrav\u0101ra]] <br/> \u0cb6\u0cc1\u0c95\u0ccd\u0cb0\u0cb5\u0cbe\u0cb0\n|[[Shukra|\u015aukrav\u0101ra\u1e41]] <br/> \u0c36\u0c41\u0c15\u0c4d\u0c30\u0c35\u0c3e\u0c30\u0c02 \n|[[Shukra|Velli]] <br/> \u0bb5\u0bc6\u0bb3\u0bcd\u0bb3\u0bbf\n|[[Shukra|Velli]]  <br/> \u0d35\u0d46\u0d33\u0d4d\u0d33\u0d3f \n|[[Shukra|\u015aukrav\u0101r]] <br/> \u0ab6\u0ac1\u0a95\u0acd\u0ab0\u0ab5\u0abe\u0ab0\n|[[Shukra|Shok\u1ee5rv\u0101r]]  <br /> \u0936\u094b'\u0915\u0941'\u0930\u0935\u093e\u0930 {{Nastaliq| \u0634\u06c6\u06a9\u0655\u0631\u0648\u0627\u0631}}\n|-\n|7\n|[[Shani|\u015aani]]v\u0101sara <br/> \u0936\u0928\u093f\u0935\u093e\u0938\u0930\n|[[Saturday]]/dies [[Saturn (mythology)|Saturnis]]\n|[[Shani|\u015aani]] = [[Saturn]]\n|[[Shani|\u015aaniv\u0101r]] <br/> \u0936\u0928\u093f\u0935\u093e\u0930\n|[[Shani|Sanichchar]] <br/> \u0938\u0928\u093f\u091a\u094d\u091a\u0930\n|[[Shani|\u015aan\u012bv\u0101r]] <br/> \u0a38\u0a3c\u0a28\u0a40\u0a35\u0a3e\u0a30 <br/> [[Shani|Chhanicchharav\u0101r]] <br/> \u0a1b\u0a28\u0a3f\u0a71\u0a1a\u0a30\u0a35\u0a3e\u0a30\n|[[Shani|\u015a\u00f4nib\u0101r]] <br/> \u09b6\u09a8\u09bf\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\n|[[Shani|\u015a\u00f4nib\u0101r]] <br/> {{font|\ua821\ua818\ua824\ua81b\ua823\ua81e|font=Surma|size=18px}}\n|[[Shani|C\u00f3nibar]]\n|[[Shani|X\u00f4nib\u0101r]] <br/> \u09b6\u09a8\u09bf\u09ac\u09be\u09f0\n|[[Shani|\u015aaniv\u0101ra]] <br/> \u0936\u0928\u093f\u0935\u093e\u0930\n|[[Shani|Sanibar]] <br/> \u0936\u0928\u093f\u0935\u093e\u0930\n|[[Shani|\u015a\u00f4nib\u0101r\u00f4]] <br/> \u0b36\u0b28\u0b3f\u0b2c\u0b3e\u0b30\n|[[Shani|\u015aaniv\u0101ra]] <br/> \u0cb6\u0ca8\u0cbf\u0cb5\u0cbe\u0cb0\n|[[Shani|\u015aaniv\u0101ra\u1e41]] <br/> \u0c36\u0c28\u0c3f\u0c35\u0c3e\u0c30\u0c02 \n|[[Shani]] <br/> \u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bbf\n|[[Shani]] <br/> \u0d36\u0d28\u0d3f\n|[[Shani|\u015aaniv\u0101r]] <br/> \u0ab6\u0aa8\u0abf\u0ab5\u0abe\u0ab0\n|Ba\u0163\u0117v\u0101r<br />\u092c\u091f\u0941'\u0935\u093e\u0930 {{Nastaliq| \u0628\u0679 \u0648\u0627\u0631}}\n|}\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\nThe term '''-v\u0101sara''' is often realised as '''v\u0101ra''' or '''vaar''' in [[Sanskrit]]-derived and influenced languages. There are many variations of the names in the regional languages, mostly using alternate names of the celestial bodies involved.\n\n===Five limbs of time===\nThe complete Indian calendars contain five ''angas'' or parts of information: lunar day (tithi), solar day (diwas), [[Asterism (astronomy)|asterism]] (naksatra), planetary joining (yoga) and astronomical period (karanam). This structure gives the calendar the name ''Panchangam''.<ref name=\"Klostermaier2007p490\"/> The first two are discussed above.\n\n====Yoga====\n{{Refimprove section|date=March 2010}}\nThe [[Sanskrit]] word Yoga means \"union, joining, attachment\", but in astronomical context, this word means latitudinal and longitudinal information. The longitude of the sun and the longitude of the moon are added, and normalised to a value ranging between 0\u00b0 to 360\u00b0 (if greater than 360, one subtracts 360). This sum is divided into 27 parts. Each part will now equal 800' (where ' is the symbol of the [[arcminute]] which means 1/60 of a degree). These parts are called the ''yogas''. They are labelled:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n# Vi\u1e63kambha\n# Pr\u012bti\n# \u0100yu\u015bm\u0101n\n# Saubh\u0101gya\n# \u015aobhana\n# Atiga\u1e47\u1e0da\n# Sukarma\n# [[Dhrti]]\n# \u015a\u016bla\n# Ga\u1e47\u1e0da\n# [[V\u1e5bddhi]]\n# [[Dhruva]]\n# Vy\u0101ghat\u0101\n# Har\u1e63a\u1e47a\n# [[Vajra]]\n# [[Siddhi]]\n# Vyatip\u0101ta\n# Variyas\n# Parigha\n# [[\u015aiva]]\n# [[Siddha]]\n# S\u0101dhya\n# \u015aubha\n# \u015aukla\n# [[Brahma]]\n# M\u0101hendra\n# Vaidh\u1e5bti\n{{div col end}}\nAgain, minor variations may exist. The ''yoga'' that is active during sunrise of a day is the prevailing ''yoga'' for the day.\n\n====Kara\u1e47a====\nA '''kara\u1e47a''' is half of a '''[[tithi]]'''. To be precise, a kara\u1e47a is the time required for the angular distance between the sun and the moon to increase in steps of 6\u00b0 starting from 0\u00b0. (Compare with the definition of a tithi.)\n\nSince the tithis are 30 in number, and since 1 tithi = 2 kara\u1e47as, therefore one would logically expect there to be 60 kara\u1e47as. But there are only 11 such kara\u1e47as which fill up those slots to accommodate for those 30 tithis. There are actually 4 \"fixed\" (sthira) kara\u1e47as and 7 \"repeating\" (cara) kara\u1e47as.\n\nThe 4\n# \u015aakuni (\u0936\u0915\u0941\u0928\u093f)\n# Catu\u1e63p\u0101da (\u091a\u0924\u0941\u0937\u094d\u092a\u093e\u0926)\n# [[N\u0101ga]] (\u0928\u093e\u0917)\n# Ki\u1e43stughna(\u0915\u093f\u0902\u0938\u094d\u0924\u0941\u0918\u094d\u0928)\n\nThe 7 \"repeating\" kara\u1e47as are:<ref name=\"Burgess1989\">{{cite book|author=Ebenezer Burgess|title=S\u00fbrya-Siddh\u00e2nta: A Text-book of Hindu Astronomy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W0Uo_-_iizwC&pg=PA107|year=1989|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-0612-2|pages=107\u2013}}</ref>\n# [[Vava]] or Bava (\u092c\u0935)\n# Valava or B\u0101lava (\u092c\u093e\u0932\u0935)\n# Kaulava (\u0915\u094c\u0932\u0935)\n# Taitila or Taitula (\u0924\u0948\u0924\u093f\u0932)\n# [[Gara]] or Garaja (\u0917\u0930\u091c)\n# Va\u1e47ija (\u0935\u0923\u093f\u091c)\n# Vi\u1e63\u1e6di ([[Bhadra (Hindu calendar)|Bhadra]]) (\u092d\u0926\u094d\u0930\u093e)\n* Now the first half of the 1st ''tithi'' (of \u015aukla Pak\u1e63a) is always ''Ki\u1e43tughna kara\u1e47a''. Hence this '''kara\u1e47a''' is \"fixed\".\n* Next, the 7-repeating kara\u1e47as repeat eight times to cover the next 56 half-''tithis''. Thus these are the \"repeating\" (cara) kara\u1e47as.\n* The 3 remaining half-''tithis'' take the remaining \"fixed\" kara\u1e47as in order. Thus these are also \"fixed\" (sthira).\n* Thus one gets 60 kara\u1e47as from those 11 preset kara\u1e47as.\n\nThe Vedic day begins at sunrise. The kara\u1e47a at sunrise of a particular day shall be the prevailing kara\u1e47a for the whole day.\n(citation needed )\n\n====Nakshatra====\n\n[[Nakshatras]] are divisions of ecliptic, each 13\u00b0 20', starting from 0\u00b0 Aries. The purnima of each month is synchronised with a nakshatra.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\n==Festival calendar: solar and lunar dates==\nMany holidays in the Hindu, Buddhist and Jaina traditions are based on the lunar cycles in the lunisolar timekeeping with foundations in the Hindu calendar system. A few holidays, however, are based on the solar cycle, such as the [[Vaisakhi]], [[Pongal (festival)|Pongal]] and those associated with Sankranti.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Peter J. Claus|author2=Sarah Diamond|author3=Margaret Ann Mills|title=South Asian Folklore: An Encyclopedia : Afghanistan, Bangladesh, India, Nepal, Pakistan, Sri Lanka|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ienxrTPHzzwC&pg=PA91|year=2003|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-93919-5|pages=91\u201393}}</ref> The dates of the lunar cycle based festivals vary significantly on the Gregorian calendar and at times by several weeks.The solar cycle based ancient Indian festivals almost always fall on the same Gregorian date every year and if they vary in an exceptional year, it is by one day.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Sewell|author2=\u015aa\u1e45kara B\u0101lakr\u0325sh\u1e47a D\u012bkshita|title=The Indian Calendar: With Tables for the Conversion of Hindu and Muhammadan Into A.D. Dates, and Vice Versa|url=https://archive.org/details/indiancalendarwi00sewerich|year=1896|publisher=S. Sonnenschein |pages=[https://archive.org/details/indiancalendarwi00sewerich/page/9 9]\u201312}}</ref>\n\n==Regional variants==\nThe Indian Calendar Reform Committee, appointed in 1952, identified more than thirty well-developed calendars, in use across different parts of India.<ref name=\"Klostermaier2007p490\"/>\n\nVariants include the lunar emphasizing ''Vikrama'', the ''Shalivahana'' calendars, as well as the solar emphasizing [[Tamil calendar]] and [[Malayalam calendar]]. The two calendars most widely used today are the ''[[Vikram Samvat|Vikrama]]'' calendar, which is in followed in western and [[northern India]] as well as [[Nepal]], and the [[Shalivahana era|Shalivahana Shaka]]  calendar which is followed in the [[Deccan]] region of India (Comprising present day Indian states of [[Telangana]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Karnataka]], [[Maharashtra]], and [[Goa]]).<ref name=\"Underhill1921\">{{cite book|author=Muriel Marion Underhill|title=The Hindu Religious Year|url=https://archive.org/details/pli.kerala.rare.23377|year=1921|publisher=Association Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/pli.kerala.rare.23377/page/n12 15]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{col div|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Hindu astrology]]\n* [[Hindu units of time|Hindu chronology]]\n* [[Hindu units of measurement]]\n* [[List of Hindu festivals]]\n* [[Panchangam]]\n* [[Panjika]]\n* [[Ancient Vedic units of measurement]]\n* [[Perpetual Calendar of 800 Years]]\n* [[Pambu Panchangam]]\n* [[Kollam era]]\n* [[List of Hindu Empires and Dynasties]]{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book|ref=harv |author=Kim Plofker|title=Mathematics in India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DHvThPNp9yMC |year=2009 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=0-691-12067-6 }}\n*{{cite journal | last=Pingree | first=David | title=The Mesopotamian Origin of Early Indian Mathematical Astronomy | journal=Journal for the History of Astronomy | publisher=SAGE | volume=4 | issue=1 | year=1973 | doi=10.1177/002182867300400102 | ref= harv| bibcode=1973JHA.....4....1P }}\n*{{cite book|last=Pingree |first= David | title= Jyotih\u015b\u0101stra : Astral and Mathematical Literature| publisher= Otto Harrassowitz| year= 1981| isbn= 978-3447021654 }}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|author=Yukio Ohashi|editor=Johannes Andersen|title=Highlights of Astronomy, Volume 11B|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gQYscrT0fgQC|year=1999|publisher=Springer Science|isbn=978-0-7923-5556-4}}\n*{{cite journal|ref=harv|author=Yukio Ohashi| title=Development of Astronomical Observations in Vedic and post-Vedic India| year=1993|journal=Indian Journal of History of Science|volume=28|number=3}}\n*{{cite book| author=Maurice Winternitz| authorlink=Moriz Winternitz| title=History of Indian Literature, Volume 1| year=1963| publisher=Motilal Banarsidass| isbn=978-81-208-0056-4}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Reingold and Dershowitz, ''[[Calendrical Calculations|Calendrical Calculations, Millennium Edition]]'', [[Cambridge University Press]], latest 2nd edition 3rd printing released November 2004. {{ISBN|0-521-77752-6}}\n* S. Balachandra Rao, ''Indian Astronomy: An Introduction'', Universities Press, Hyderabad, 2000.\n* Rai Bahadur Pandit Gaurishankar Hirachand Ojha, ''The Paleography of India'', 2 ed., Ajmer, 1918, reprinted Manshuram Manoharlal publishers, 1993.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://nepalicalendar.rat32.com/ Hindu Calendar of Nepal] The Official Hindu Nepali Calendar\n* [http://www.cc.kyoto-su.ac.jp/~yanom/pancanga/ Kyoto University Gregorian \u2013 Saka \u2013 Vikrami Calendar Converter Tool], M. YANO and M. FUSHIMI\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170524154539/http://www.bsswebsite.me.uk/Daysanddates/indiandate.htm Converter: Gregorian and 1957 Normalized Indian Calendar], Shalivahana Hindu calendar, United Kingdom\n* [http://www.math.harvard.edu/computing/javascript/Calendar/ Hindu Calendar to Julian / Hebrew / Islamic / Mayan / French / ISO 8601 Converter], Harvard University\n* [http://nepcal.com/ Hindu Calendar of Nepal] The Official Hindu Calendar of Nepal\n* [https://www.odiaweb.in/odia-calendar-2019/ Hindu Odia Calendar] The most followed Hindu Odia Calendar of Odisha, India\n*[https://panchang.astrosage.com/calendars/hindu-calendar?date=2020 Hindu Calendar 2020] Fasting Dates & Festivals for New Delhi, India\n* [https://www.drikpanchang.com/panchang/month-panchang.html/https://www.drikpanchang.com/ Accurate Hindu Calendar/Drik Panchang]\n* [https://www.todaycalendar.co/ Today Marathi Calendar current year]\n* [https://kultejas.blogspot.com/2019/10/marathi-kalnirnay-calendar-2020-marathi.html Marathi Kalnirnay Calendar 2020]\n\n{{Hindu calendar}}\n{{calendars}}\n{{HinduFestivals}}\n{{Hindudharma}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hindu Calendar}}\n[[Category:Hindu calendar| ]]\n[[Category:Hindu astronomy|Calendar]]\n[[Category:Hindu astrology|Calendar]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "V2Blast", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Copyedit (minor)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindu_calendar"}
{"title_page": "Assent of faith", "text_new": "'''Assent of faith''' or '''full assent of faith''' is belief in [[Catholic dogma]], shown by obedience of faith.<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s1c3a1.htm Catechism: Man's Response to God] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223070050/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s1c3a1.htm |date=February 23, 2014 }}</ref> The exemplar of obedience of faith is the [[Virgin Mary]],<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p122a3p2.htm#494 Catechism: \"Let it be done to me according to your word. . .\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227101719/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p122a3p2.htm#494 |date=February 27, 2014 }}</ref> who assented to the Word of God at the [[Annunciation]]:<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s1c3a1.htm#148 Catechism: \"Blessed is she who believed\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223070050/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s1c3a1.htm#148 |date=February 23, 2014 }}</ref> \"Let it be done to me according to your word.\"<ref>[http://biblehub.com/luke/1-38.htm Luke 1:38]</ref> Assent of faith does not rest \"on a mass of probabilities\"<ref>[http://papalencyclicals.net/Pius10/p10lamen.htm LAMENTABILI SANE, Propositons 25]</ref> but on God,<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s2c1p1.htm#215 Catechism: God is Truth] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424175251/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s2c1p1.htm#215 |date=April 24, 2014 }}</ref> and the Church can and does demand assent of faith to her judgments,<ref>[http://papalencyclicals.net/Pius10/p10lamen.htm LAMENTABILI SANE, Propositons 7]</ref> as is her right and duty.<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s1c2a2.htm#85 Catechism: The Magisterium of the Church] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208112021/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s1c2a2.htm#85 |date=February 8, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Catholic theology and doctrine]]\n[[Category:Catholic doctrines]]\n[[Category:Dogma]]\n\n\n{{RC-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Assent of faith''' or '''full assent of faith''' is belief in [[Roman Catholic dogma]], shown by obedience of faith.<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s1c3a1.htm Catechism: Man's Response to God] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223070050/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s1c3a1.htm |date=February 23, 2014 }}</ref> The exemplar of obedience of faith is the [[Virgin Mary]],<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p122a3p2.htm#494 Catechism: \"Let it be done to me according to your word. . .\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227101719/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p122a3p2.htm#494 |date=February 27, 2014 }}</ref> who assented to the Word of God at the [[Annunciation]]:<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s1c3a1.htm#148 Catechism: \"Blessed is she who believed\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223070050/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s1c3a1.htm#148 |date=February 23, 2014 }}</ref> \"Let it be done to me according to your word.\"<ref>[http://biblehub.com/luke/1-38.htm Luke 1:38]</ref> Assent of faith does not rest \"on a mass of probabilities\"<ref>[http://papalencyclicals.net/Pius10/p10lamen.htm LAMENTABILI SANE, Propositons 25]</ref> but on God,<ref>[https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s2c1p1.htm#215 Catechism: God is Truth] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424175251/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ccc_css/archive/catechism/p1s2c1p1.htm#215 |date=April 24, 2014 }}</ref> and the Church ca